v_x = v_0 \cos \theta
\]

Given that \( v_0 = 50 \) m/s and \( \theta = 53^\circ \), so:

\[
v_x = 50 \times \cos(53^\circ)
\]

I know that \( \cos(53^\circ) = 0.6 \), so:

\[
v_x = 50 \times 0.6 = 30 \text{ m/s}
\]

Now, the time \( t \) it takes to cover the horizontal distance \( l = 60 \) meters is:

\[
t = \frac{l}{v_x} = \frac{60}{30} = 2 \text{ seconds}
\]